21. Look at this variable definition trap. What does this declare?
#include <iostream>
struct Widget {
    Widget() { std::cout << "Created"; }
};
int main() {
    Widget w();
}
A) Prints "Created"
B) Declares a function named w that returns a Widget.
C) Compilation error due to invalid brackets.
D) Undefined Behavior.

22. What happens when you use post-increment vs pre-increment inside a loop evaluation?
int i = 0;
while(i++ < 3) {
    std::cout << i;
}
A) 012
B) 123
C) 1234
D) 0123

23. Polymorphism in C++ has conditions. What does this code print?
struct Base {
    void print() { std::cout << "Base"; }
};
struct Derived : Base {
    void print() { std::cout << "Derived"; }
};
int main() {
    Base* b = new Derived();
    b->print();
    delete b;
}
A) Base
B) Derived
C) Compile error
D) Runtime crash

25. Watch out for order of evaluation quirks:
int a = 1;
a = a++ + ++a;
std::cout << a;
A) 4
B) 5
C) Undefined/Unspecified Behavior
D) 3

26. Destructors and polymorphism require care. What is the issue here?
struct B { ~B() {} };
struct D : B { ~D() { std::cout << "Destroyed"; } };
int main() {
    B* ptr = new D();
    delete ptr;
}
A) Prints "Destroyed" safely
B) Compilation Error
C) Undefined behavior because destructor is not virtual
D) Memory leak, but perfectly defined behavior

27. What is the output of this unsigned wrap-around statement?
unsigned int x = 0;
x--;
std::cout << (x > -1);
A) 0 (False)
B) 1 (True)
C) Compile error due to negative value comparison
D) Undefined Behavior

29. Vector reallocations invalidate iterators. What happens here?
#include <vector>
std::vector<int> v = {1};
auto it = v.begin();
v.push_back(2);
std::cout << *it;
A) 1
B) 2
C) Undefined Behavior
D) Segmentation fault safely aborted by compiler

